The Riemann Hypothesis as a Dynamical Rigidity Problem
Zero Motion, Local Barriers, and Heat-Flow Structure in the de Bruijn–Newman Family

Abstract
--------

We study the motion of real zeros under heat-type deformations associated with the Riemann ξ-function and the de Bruijn–Newman family. Starting from the exact zero-tracking identity

    ṫ_i = - F_λ / F_t (t_i),

we derive the local singular structure of zero motion near simple real zeros. In the repulsive heat-flow convention, neighbouring zeros interact through a leading Hadamard pole term

    ṫ_i = 2 Σ_{j≠i} 1/(t_i - t_j) + E_i,

where E_i denotes the regular external contribution.

Numerical experiments on finite zero windows reveal a robust reduced-flow structure. In the healthy regime, the velocity field is well described by a two-mode geometry consisting of a Hadamard repulsion mode and a secondary density-balancing mode. Across 252 tested windows, 230 were classified as strong geometry, 5 as borderline, and 17 as weak. The weak windows were not random: they occurred exactly when the minimum gap satisfied

    g_min / Δ̄ < 0.14.

A force decomposition showed that these weak windows are local-pair dominated: the minimum-gap pair contributes approximately 80% of the velocity norm, while the compressive tail contributes only about 1% of the adjacent-pair term. Local rescaling does not rescue these windows under the correct time-scale transformation, indicating that the weak sector is a genuine local-pair regime rather than a global normalisation artefact.

We then formulate a finite-model barrier theorem. In the reduced repulsive model,

    ṫ_i = 2 Σ_{j≠i} 1/(t_i - t_j),

the neighbouring gap g_i = t_{i+1} - t_i satisfies

    ġ_i = 4/g_i
           - 2g_i Σ_{j≠i,i+1}
             1/(|t_{i+1}-t_j| |t_i-t_j|).

Thus a sufficiently isolated small gap is forced open by the singular adjacent-pair term. More generally, a collapsing cluster of r real zeros has internal variance derivative

    V̇_int = 2r(r-1),

so a finite real-zero cluster cannot collapse under repulsive log-gas dynamics plus a locally Lipschitz external field.

Subsequent sign and isolation audits show that the increasing-λ de Bruijn–Newman flow has the repulsive adjacent-pair sign, and that any finite real-zero collision at finite t and finite λ is locally isolated and admits a Weierstrass factorisation. Therefore the local Lipschitz bridge for finite isolated clusters is not the main remaining obstruction.

However, this local barrier does not by itself prove Λ ≤ 0. A positive Newman boundary is locally a square-root birth when viewed in increasing λ: for λ < Λ a complex conjugate pair exists, at λ = Λ a double real zero occurs, and for λ > Λ two real zeros separate under the repulsive flow. This local behaviour is compatible with the zero-motion law.

The proof target has therefore shifted from local finite-cluster exclusion to a global obstruction against positive Newman-boundary birth. Current numerical work has moved to kernel and Jensen-polynomial structure. Lambda-grid Sturm audits verified hyperbolicity of finite Jensen polynomials through degrees 21,...,30, n=0,...,40, with 3280/3280 passes, and partial extension through degrees 31,...,40, n=0,...,20, at λ=0 and λ=10^-6, with 420/420 additional passes. Structural diagnostics show that the coefficient sequence is not ordinary Stieltjes-positive, but its Hankel determinants obey a signed pattern

    (-1)^(m(m+1)/2) det(A_{i+j+s}) > 0

for the tested ordinary and shifted Hankel families. This points toward a signed Hankel / sign-regular / oscillatory-total-positivity mechanism as the next theoretical target.


1. Setup
--------

Let ξ(s) denote the Riemann xi-function and define

    Ξ(t) = ξ(1/2 + it).

The de Bruijn–Newman family may be written formally as

    Ξ_λ(t) = ∫_0^∞ e^{λx²} Φ(x) cos(tx) dx,

with the heat-type identity

    ∂_λ Ξ_λ(t) = -∂_{tt} Ξ_λ(t),

up to the chosen normalisation convention.

More generally, let F(λ,t) be a real entire function, real-valued on ℝ, analytic in (λ,t), and satisfying a heat-type evolution

    F_λ = κ F_{tt}.

The sign of κ determines whether the induced zero motion is attractive or repulsive. The repulsive direction is the relevant convention for the barrier calculations below.

Let

    t_1(λ) < t_2(λ) < ...

denote real simple zeros of F(λ,·), where such an ordering exists.


2. Exact zero tracking
----------------------

Lemma 2.1 — Zero tracking

If t_i(λ_0) is a simple zero of F(λ_0,·), then there is a unique local C¹ trajectory t_i(λ) such that

    F(λ,t_i(λ)) = 0.

Moreover,

    ṫ_i = - F_λ / F_t (λ,t_i).

Proof.

Differentiate

    F(λ,t_i(λ)) = 0

with respect to λ:

    F_λ + ṫ_i F_t = 0.

Since F_t ≠ 0 at a simple zero,

    ṫ_i = - F_λ / F_t.


3. Local Hadamard pole structure
--------------------------------

Assume F admits a local factorisation near its simple zeros,

    F(t) = e^{H(t)} Π_m (t - t_m),

with H analytic in the local region of interest.

At a simple zero t_i,

    F_{tt}/F_t (t_i)
      =
    2H'(t_i) + 2Σ_{m≠i} 1/(t_i - t_m).

Therefore, for a heat-type evolution F_λ = κF_{tt},

    ṫ_i
      =
    -2κ [ H'(t_i) + Σ_{m≠i} 1/(t_i - t_m) ].

In the repulsive convention, rescale the parameter so that the singular part becomes

    ṫ_i
      =
    2Σ_{m≠i} 1/(t_i - t_m) + E_i,

where E_i denotes the regular external contribution.

This is the formal source of the reduced finite-zero model used in the numerical experiments.


4. Pair-gap equation in the finite reduced model
------------------------------------------------

Consider the finite reduced repulsive model

    ṫ_i = 2Σ_{j≠i} 1/(t_i - t_j).

Let

    g_i = t_{i+1} - t_i.

Then

    ġ_i
      =
    4/g_i
    -
    2g_i Σ_{j≠i,i+1}
    1/(|t_{i+1}-t_j| |t_i-t_j|).

The first term is the singular adjacent-pair repulsion. The second term is the compressive tail from all other zeros.

Thus the finite-model gap law has the form

    ġ_i = 4/g_i - C_i g_i

with

    C_i =
    2Σ_{j≠i,i+1}
    1/(|t_{i+1}-t_j| |t_i-t_j|).

If C_i is locally bounded, then g_i cannot vanish in finite time.


5. Controlled-error pair barrier
--------------------------------

Lemma 5.1 — Pair no-collapse under linear error

Let g(λ)>0 satisfy

    ġ ≥ A/g - K(λ)g,

where A>0, K(λ)≥0, and K∈L¹_loc. Then g cannot reach zero in finite λ-time.

Proof.

Let

    h = g².

Then

    ḣ = 2g ġ ≥ 2A - 2K(λ)h.

So

    ḣ + 2K(λ)h ≥ 2A.

Multiplying by the integrating factor

    μ(λ) = exp( ∫_0^λ 2K(u) du )

gives

    (μh)' ≥ 2Aμ.

Hence

    h(λ)
      ≥
    μ(λ)^(-1) [ h(0) + 2A∫_0^λ μ(s) ds ].

The right-hand side is strictly positive for finite λ. Therefore g(λ)>0, and collision is impossible.


6. Local-minimum barrier in the finite model
--------------------------------------------

Let

    g_min = η Δ̄,

where Δ̄ is the mean gap in the finite window.

Let the second-smallest gap be

    g_second = a Δ̄.

A conservative infinite-tail estimate shows that a sufficient barrier condition is

    η < a.

Equivalently,

    g_min < g_second.

Numerically, across 252 tested finite windows, every minimum gap satisfied this strict local-minimum condition and every minimum gap had

    ġ_min > 0.

For the weak-geometry windows specifically:

    g_min / Δ̄ ≈ 0.109–0.135,

with

    ġ_min ≈ 32.4–37.9.

The adjacent-pair term dominated:

    |tail| / |pair| ≈ 0.0066–0.0157.

Thus the weak windows are not collapse-threat windows. They are strong local reopening cases.


7. Cluster-variance barrier
---------------------------

The pair barrier handles isolated two-zero collisions. A possible remaining failure mode is simultaneous collapse of a cluster of r adjacent zeros.

Let

    x_1 < ... < x_r

be a finite cluster and define

    x̄ = (1/r) Σ_{k=1}^r x_k,

    V = Σ_{k=1}^r (x_k - x̄)^2.

Assume the cluster evolves by

    ẋ_k =
    2Σ_{ℓ≠k} 1/(x_k - x_ℓ) + E_k.

The internal repulsive part satisfies the exact identity

    V̇_int = 2r(r-1).

Derivation.

Let

    y_k = x_k - x̄.

Then

    Σ_k y_k = 0

and

    V̇ = 2Σ_k y_k ẋ_k.

For the internal repulsive part,

    ẋ_{k,int} =
    2Σ_{ℓ≠k} 1/(x_k - x_ℓ).

Thus

    V̇_int =
    4Σ_k y_k Σ_{ℓ≠k} 1/(x_k - x_ℓ).

Pair the unordered terms k<ℓ. Each pair contributes

    y_k/(x_k-x_ℓ) + y_ℓ/(x_ℓ-x_k)
      =
    (y_k-y_ℓ)/(x_k-x_ℓ)
      =
    1.

There are r(r-1)/2 unordered pairs, so

    V̇_int = 2r(r-1).

Now assume the external field is Lipschitz across the cluster:

    |E_k - E_m| ≤ L|x_k - x_m|.

Then

    |V̇_ext|
      =
    |2Σ_k y_k E_k|
      ≤
    2LV.

Therefore

    V̇ ≥ 2r(r-1) - 2LV.

By the same integrating-factor argument as in Lemma 5.1, V cannot reach zero in finite time.


8. Bridge condition for the full de Bruijn–Newman flow
------------------------------------------------------

The earlier reduced-flow analysis suggested that the main analytic bridge was to prove local Lipschitz control of the external logarithmic derivative near a hypothetical finite real-zero collision. That bridge has now been sharpened.

For the de Bruijn–Newman family,

    Ξ_λ(t) = ∫_0^∞ e^{λx²} Φ(x) cos(tx) dx,

one has

    ∂_λ Ξ_λ(t) = -∂_{tt} Ξ_λ(t).

If x_i(λ) is a simple real zero, then

    ẋ_i
      =
    - ∂_λ Ξ_λ / ∂_t Ξ_λ (x_i)
      =
    Ξ_{λ,tt} / Ξ_{λ,t} (x_i).

Using the local product expansion near simple real zeros,

    Ξ_λ(t) = e^{H(t)} Π_j (t - x_j),

the singular part of the zero velocity is

    ẋ_i
      =
    2Σ_{j≠i} 1/(x_i - x_j)
    +
    2H'(x_i).

Thus increasing Newman λ gives the repulsive adjacent-pair sign. For a neighbouring pair x<y, with g=y-x, the singular contribution to the gap equation is

    ġ = 4/g + regular terms.

This verifies that the reduced repulsive convention has the correct local sign for increasing λ.

Now suppose a finite real-zero collision occurs at finite (λ_*,t_*). Since Ξ_{λ_*} is entire and nonzero as a function, the zero at t_* has finite multiplicity and is locally isolated. By the Weierstrass preparation theorem,

    Ξ_λ(t) = U(λ,t) W(λ,t),

where U is analytic and nonzero, and W is a finite-degree polynomial in t whose zeros describe the local cluster.

For nearby simple real branches x_1(λ),...,x_r(λ),

    Ξ_λ(t)
      =
    U(λ,t) Π_{k=1}^r (t - x_k(λ)).

Therefore the external factor is analytic and nonzero. A local branch of log U exists, and the external logarithmic derivative has bounded t-derivative on compact neighbourhoods. Hence the external field is locally Lipschitz across the finite cluster.

Thus, for finite isolated real-zero clusters, the local bridge condition is automatic under the standard analytic assumptions.

The local result is:

    finite isolated real-zero clusters cannot collapse in the increasing-λ repulsive direction.

This is a genuine local barrier result, but it is not yet a global proof of Λ ≤ 0.


