10. Interpretation of the reduced-flow regimes
----------------------------------------------

The reduced finite-zero model exhibits two distinct regimes.


10.1 Healthy distributed regime
-------------------------------

When no gap is extremely compressed, the velocity field is distributed across the window. The flow is well described by a two-mode structure:

    1. Hadamard repulsion mode
    2. density-balancing mode

This is the regime where rank-2 geometry and coefficient closure behave well.


10.2 Small-gap local-pair regime
--------------------------------

When

    g_min / Δ̄ < 0.14,

the flow becomes dominated by the minimum adjacent pair. This weakens the global two-mode geometry but strengthens the local reopening barrier.

The weak geometry therefore does not indicate collapse. It indicates that the local singular pair interaction has become the dominant stabilising mechanism.


11. Relation to complex-zero formation
--------------------------------------

For a real entire family analytic in the deformation parameter, creation or annihilation of a nonreal conjugate pair occurs through a multiple real zero. Locally, near a generic double zero,

    F(t,λ)
      =
    U(t,λ)
    [
      (t-t_*)² - c(λ-λ_*)
    ],

with U(t_*,λ_*) ≠ 0.

For the Newman heat sign

    F_λ = -F_{tt},

the local normal form is, to leading order,

    F(t,λ)
      =
    U
    [
      (t-t_*)² - 2(λ-λ_*)
    ].

Thus:

    λ < λ_*:
        complex conjugate pair,

    λ = λ_*:
        double real zero,

    λ > λ_*:
        two real zeros.

The corresponding real-zero gap behaves like

    g(λ) ~ sqrt(8(λ-λ_*)).

This is compatible with the repulsive adjacent-pair equation

    ġ ~ 4/g.

Therefore the local repulsion law does not forbid a positive Newman boundary. It describes the real-zero side after the pair has already been born.

The local finite-cluster barrier excludes collapse of already-real zeros as λ increases. It does not, by itself, exclude a square-root birth at a positive boundary.

The remaining problem is therefore global:

    exclude a positive square-root birth boundary λ_* > 0.


12. Relation to the de Bruijn–Newman constant
---------------------------------------------

The de Bruijn–Newman constant Λ marks the transition between the real-zero and nonreal-zero regimes of the de Bruijn–Newman family.

The local audits establish:

    1. increasing Newman λ has the repulsive adjacent-pair sign;
    2. finite real-zero collisions are locally isolated;
    3. the external factor near a finite collision is analytic and nonzero;
    4. finite real clusters cannot collapse under the repulsive zero-flow law plus Lipschitz external field.

These facts are compatible with the standard Newman picture: increasing λ regularises the zero set, while decreasing λ is the dangerous direction.

However, a hypothetical Λ > 0 boundary is not ruled out by local repulsion alone. At such a boundary, viewed in increasing λ, the event is a birth of two real zeros from a complex conjugate pair, not a collapse of real zeros.

Thus the proof route cannot stop at local no-collapse.

The current target is:

    find a global obstruction to a positive Newman boundary.

Recent work has therefore shifted toward kernel, Jensen-polynomial, and signed-total-positivity diagnostics.

Newman's theorem gives

    Λ ≥ 0.

A proof of

    Λ ≤ 0

would require showing that no positive square-root birth boundary can occur.


